#!/usr/bin/perl

=pod

NOTES:

Best notes on this are Farhan's:
http://mysqldatabaseadministration.blogspot.com/2007/05/pre-fetch-binlogs-to-speed-up-mysql.html

connect to slave
read slave status
read N bytes from binlog, N bytes ahead of current position
filter:
   Throw away non-replicated DBs
   throw away events of certain size (user, certain tables, ...)
   allow only certain types of statements
   throw away timestamp identical to previous timestamp
parse
convert
   UPDATE: convert to SELECT
   INSERT: convert to SELECT... where PK >= keys limit 1
      (cache table structures)
   REPLACE: convert to SELECT
   DELETE: convert to SELECT... where limit 1
   INSERT/SELECT: split into two queries
   REPLACE/SELECT: split into two queries
replay
   rewrite columns as LEFT(CONCAT(LEFT(col, 1), LEFT(col, 1)...), 1)
sleep N

Look at relay log size and file times to see how fast the slave is advancing on
average, or just watch it for a few seconds and see.

Learn which statements take a long time to execute, canonicalize them, and don't
re-execute them.  Read a file of such statements on startup.

=cut

